<p><img alt="9款茶并排品鉴" data-aspect-ratio="1 / 1" decoding="async" height="100" id="_IxNUI1VY" loading="lazy" src="/images/2011-teatasting-5.jpg" title="9款茶并排品鉴" width="100"></img></p>
<figcaption><p>9款茶并排品鉴</p></figcaption>
</figure>
<p><!--
I'm not sure how much statistical/machine-learning recommendation
techniques would really add over the obvious white/green/oolong/black
type clustering and basic user ratings ('if someone buys mostly
oolong, recommend all the 5-star oolongs to them'). All datasets are
incomplete and limited and put limits on how much can be inferred from
them...* I think it would depend on how good a dataset one could
acquire: you'd want at least a few hundred ratings over a few dozen
teas with good metadata like
name/type/price-per-oz/country/description.

* for example, tea harvests vary from year to year but when a seller
ships a tea, you don't know what year it is from; you don't know how
it was stored or for how long; for that matter, you don't know what
farm a given tea is coming from even if you are buying the same
'product' from the same seller. These may be the crucial factors which
overwhelmingly determine how people will like a particular purchase
beyond what is determined by simply being oolong/green/etc. Or they
might not.
We could imagine doing chemical analyses to try to pin down tastes to
particular concentrations or combinations of chemicals so you could
just test each batch, but what am I, a chemist? Who'd fund the initial
testing? And would consumers really appreciate accurate testing and
evaluation like that? Doesn't seem likely, they'd balk at the higher
built-in prices likely...

previous research: http://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=tea+taste+OR+flavor+factor+analysis&btnG=&hl=en&as_sdt=0%2C9

possible tea rating sources:
1. Amazon
2. http://ratetea.com/
3. http://www.teaviews.com/
4. http://steepster.com/
5. http://www.teareviewblog.com/

existing company? http://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/06/26/as-indias-teas-gain-fans-seeking-a-faster-way-to-get-it-to-them/
--></p>
</section>
